AB  - The present study investigates the possibility for the Swedish forest industry to be a supplier of biomass for cogeneration of methanol, power and heat. Simulations have been performed in ASPEN PLUS(TM) to study the potential of different ways of using biomass from the pulp mills to reduce the carbon dioxide emissions. The biomass consists of waste wood, precipitated lignin and black liquor. Two different cases are estimated: case 1, where the pulp mill has a traditional recovery system, and the feedstock to the methanol plant constitutes of waste wood and some ligning precipitated from the black liquor; and case 2, where a new recovery system called black liquor gasification is introduced into the pulp mill. Case 2 permits a more flexible energy recovery and the available biomass increases. from 65 MW to 487 MW. In both cases, the process steam demand of the reference pulp mill will be fulfilled, and no fossil fuels are used in the mill.
   The methanol is further studied as an environmentally sustainable transportation fuel to replace gasoline. In case 1, with the lower amount of biomass used for methanol production, implementing the technology in all the Swedish chemical pulp mills results in a decrease of the carbon dioxide emissions by 465,000 t/y(1) when replacing gasoline with methanol. This figure corresponds to 4 % of the carbon dioxide emissions from the Swedish vehicles. In case 2, where a new technology is introduced, the same figures amounts to 1,932,000 t/y and 16 %, respectively.
