AB  - The conflict between Hakon Hakonsson and Skule Bardsson has been a recurring theme in Norwegian medieval research. In this article, three issues will be looked at in more detail. The traditional view that Skule was outmaneuvered by the circle around Hakon will be refuted by referring to the development of the relationship between them through the 1230s and the agreements on the distribution of power that followed. Skule's desire to be king is often given as an underlying motive for his rebellion against Hakon. At the same time, many historians believe that it was the new distribution of landed estates from 1237 that was the main reason for Skule's revolt. This article will argue against both of these interpretations and give an alternative explanation. There has been a unanimous view among historians that Skule's revolt was doomed to fail. This article argues against this view by highlighting the political and military status immediately prior to the Varbelgers defeat in Oslo on 21 April 1240. What decided the war was the outcome and consequences of the battle in Oslo, one of the few decisive battles in Norway.
