AB  - This communication is drawn from the work of the European research project DayWater, which aims at the creation of an Adaptive Decision Support System for the integration of storm water source control into sustainable urban water management strategies. Source control techniques include all techniques (retention, infiltration, reuse) of treatment of stormwater near the source in contrast to end-of pipe techniques which aim at the concentration and treatment of water downstream. Thanks to this project we had the opportunity to collaborate with several stormwater 'managers' in Europe (participating countries: U.K, France, Sweden, Denmark, Germany, The Netherlands and Greece), specialists working in Water and Sewage Companies and in co-ordination institutions who have the obligation of assuring water management in river catchment areas or large metropolitan areas. In this communication we are going to present:
   The different stormwater management problems in Europe.
   The stormwater management problems in Greece
   Techniques of source control applied in European cities.
   How these techniques and policies could be applied in Greek Cities.
   In Greece in contrast to the other participating countries stormwater pollution is not perceived as a priority problem. Waste water management, promoted by European Directive (91/271/EU) and european funding, flood prevention and fresh water scarcity are priority problems. The question of treating the stormwater has not been yet evoked. Source control management of stormwater can contribute to all three problems.
   The new European Water Framework (2000/60/EC) demands the improvement of ecological status of water bodies and prescribes management of the pollution at its source. It also invites member countries in building an integrated water management policy (fresh water, waste water, storm water, bathing and other recreational activities, fisheries, industrial use etc.). Stormwater treatment is indispensable in order to reach these objectives. In most European cities source control techniques have been chosen for the treatment of stormwater because they are less expensive than massive end-of-pipe treatment installations, they are closer to the natural water cycle, they reduce the stormwater flow and they permit the expansion of cities without requesting new dimensioning and reconstruction of the existing sewer systems. Different policy instruments (taxes, special regulations and controls, information campaigns) have been applied in order to promote source control techniques.
   The main objective of this communication is to discuss the possibility of applying similar techniques and policies in Greek cities.
