AB  - The communications industry is experiencing a rapid growth in introduction and diffusion of new services and applications, particularly in the areas of wireless and broad band. This rapid growth is driven by the evolution of communications technologies and regulatory policies. The new services are also displacing some of the demands for traditional wireline services such as voice communications. To meet these increasing and shifting demands, communications service providers need to effectively forecast such demands for short term and long run in order to plan and deploy sufficient infrastructure and operations capabilities.
   Demand for wireless services are growing much faster than anything we have experienced in the past. In some countries, such as Sweden and Italy, cell phone density has already exceeded 100%. The key questions for infrastructure planners are: 1) what is the expected saturation level for wireless cell phones? How fast are we getting there? How much does it vary from country to country and why? 2) How to forecast short term demands and substitution rates for various services in a selected region.
   This paper presents the results of an analysis to forecast saturation levels for cell phones in US and a number of European countries based on trend data from 1984 through 2004, using technology diffusion models. The authors discuss the differences among the countries and some of the contributing factors such as existing infrastructure and cultural differences. The authors conclude with some of the challenges for service providers responding to the transition issues from wireline to wireless services and integration of operations across technology domains.
