AB  - The author argues that the latest elections to the European Parliament (EP) became a landmark event in the party-political landscape of the Old World. The elections confirmed the trend emerged in the beginning of the XXI century: nationalist parties almost everywhere strengthened their electoral positions. In Austria, Italy and Finland they gained solid experience of coalition work. In the Netherlands and Belgium nationalist parties managed to enter local government. To a big extent, nationalists influenced the governments in Denmark, Sweden, and, more recently, in Spain. Nationalists became active in Eastern Europe (Poland, Hungary). Their primary political interest is focused on the European Union reforms, the migration issue, the social processes in the EU, relations between Europe and the United States, China, and Russia. After the European elections in May, 2019, they created the large "Identity and Democracy" group within the European parliament. The article examines conflicting trends in the nationalist camp, the development of both centripetal and centrifugal tendencies. It is possible to assess the current situation only by considering objective and subjective factors typical both for individual countries, regions of Europe, and for the continent as a whole.
