AB  - Game meat, one of man's main sources of food in prehistoric times, now plays a relatively modest role in total food and meat consumption in most parts of the world. However, in Europe, notably in East, Central and Northern Europe, wildlife is still of considerable importance. In some countries, especially Germany, the overall output of hunted game has increased during the past several decades. The increase has been mainly with deer of various species and wild boar, whereas the population of hares and wild birds has generally decreased. In several European and overseas countries the supply of hunted game has more recently been supplemented by venison from fallow and red deer and other meats from a rapidly expanding game farming sector. Germany and Sweden keep the largest populations of farmed game in Europe. However, the forerunner of commercial deer farming has been New Zealand which keeps over a million deer, approximately half of the world's stock of farmed game animals. New Zealand has also become the leading exporter of game meat. Other major suppliers are Argentina, Australia, Poland and other countries of Central and East Europe. The largest import market is the European Union, with Germany, France, Italy and Sweden accounting for the bulk of EU imports. Prices of game meat, both hunted and farmed, are generally well above those of domestic animals. Consumption its very unevenly distributed among the various groups of population. In fact, in North America and West Europe hunters and their acquaintance consume a very large portion of total local supplies. Game farming and ranching is expected to continue its worldwide expansion, whereas the natural habitat for wildlife is shrinking, especially in developing countries. All in all, game meat will remain relatively small in global meat production, consumption and trade.
