AB  - Since many years there is a widespread use of antimicrobial agents as growth promoters in animal production to improve daily gains and feed conversion rates.
   Especially in the last 2 years - enhanced by the discussion on Avoparcin - their use is critizised more and more. Various scientific organizations and the German association of veterinary practicioners, too, demand for the ban of all antibiotic substances as feed additives. The arguments are for example the toxicity of special substances, the lower effects under optimized housing conditions, the mode of application (without veterinary prescription), incompatibilities with therapeutics (ionophores / tiamulin), the risk for residues (substances absorbed from the intestine), intoxications in non-target-species (ionophores in horses) and especially the risk of development of resistance in bacteria.
   Especially as nutritionists we must not forget that various antimicrobial feed additives have distinct disease-preventing effects, are efficient in reducing pollution (methan, nitrogen, phosphorus), and in saving nutrients. We should consider experiences obtained in Sweden, where the use of antibiotic growth promoters is prohibited since 1986.
   Is it really a sign of progress when the same substances (for example olaquindox) are used as therapeutics now (prescribed by veterinarians) in a dosage of 100 - 160 ppm (in-feed-medication), whereas in former times the upper limit was 50 ppm? Can we accept that now zinc oxide is generally used in rearing piglets in a dosage of 3000 - 4000 mg/kg diet to prevent diarrhea and higher mortality rates?
   What are the reasons that make the use of antibiotics obviously essential? It is not the small (but significant) effect on growth and feed conversion rate, it is the risk of illness, of higher mortality in young animals. of economical losses due to these factors in large herds and production units. Is it even an utopian scheme to manage the "modern" production systems (specialized units, increased herd sire, necessity of transports, grouping, and others) without the shield of antibiotics? Is there eventually a need for a more critical look on the structure of animal production that has developed in recent years?
