AB  - Possible climate change can cause changes in the forest growth rate (FGR), however, it is not the only factor of FGR changes. Two estimates of site indices H50 as stand height predictions at the reference age of 50 years were calculated for each forest stand, one on the basis of forest inventory data of 1951 (H50(1951)) and the other one of 1994 (H50,,,) using a difference equation of stand height depending on stand age, main species and site factors. The difference equation of height for Estonian state forests was elaborated on the basis of the set of single records of forest inventory data per each of 511 514 stands described in 1984-1993. Using the new dynamic data set (2 records per stand with time interval 43 years), the change in site index from 1951 to 1994 (difference H50(1994) - H50(1951)) was calculated and used as dependent variable to indicate and to analyse the actual change in forest growth.
   On the basis of 10514 sub-compartment data records, an average increase of 2.1 meters of site index H50 was calculated, as well as a remarkably high standard deviation of 3.6 meters. Increase in site index depends on many factors, mostly on drainage, main species, change of stand generation and forest district. Average increase of site index H50 was 2.1 meters for pine stands, 1.4 meters for spruce stands and 2.5 meters for birch stands.
